---
Ushabti jurisprudence examines the Saltbound Custodians with particular interest because the case is the nearest analog in mortal institutional history to the Ushabti's own situation: a body whose authority derives from a mandate that outlasted its original principal, continuing under their own best interpretation.
The difference is that the Ushabti were given autonomous will to adapt their interpretation as conditions change; the Custodians were converted to undead form under a Perpetual Custody mandate providing no mechanism for interpretation revision.
They are executing the mandate exactly as written, in conditions the mandate did not anticipate, with no authority to update.
The Ushabti find this more sympathetic than most races do: the alternative to the Custodians' precise mandate execution would be arbitrary action without legal foundation, which is the worse failure mode.
Precision without authority to adapt is preferable to adaptation without precision — but it is not the same as justice.
